5:00 pm 3-9-21 I became instantly exhausted and had fatigue. I got chills and ran a 99.8 fever. I went to bed and about 5 hours later my fever broke and I felt fine in the morning when I woke up. 9:30pm on 3-13-21 I found both of my thighs bright red. It was not itchy, but it was warm to the touch. 7:45pm on 3-14-21 My butt cheeks were bright red and warm to the touch. Then about 30 minutes later my thighs became red. Everything red started itching was raised like hives. I found three dots on my arm and later those spread into large spots of hives. Then over the next 9 hours, a new spot would start, it would spread, then it would itch like crazy. I took 25mg of Diphenhydramine at 8pm. I took another 50mg at 10 when I was having no relief and it continued to spread. At 1:15am both of my hands and wrists had hives and these hurt and itched the most because they were swollen and hard to bend. At 3am both of my feet started to flair up. Finally around 5am the hives stopped. I was not able to sleep through it. I did not ever have a fever, I checked that 4 times. I also did not have trouble breathing or have any swelling on my face. 3-15-21 @ 9:20am I went to see my doctor. All of my vitals were good. All of my hives were gone. He put me on Prednisone in case it came back and at 11am I took 4 pills and went to bed. I woke up 2 hours later and my feet were itching again. My left foot broke out in hives bad. It lasted for over an hour. My toes were hard to bend. 4:34pm on 3-15-21 currently I don't have any hives and I am tired. I thoroughly thought through everything that I have eaten, worn, and used, and I have changed nothing over the past 2 weeks.

Per HCW, she developed flu-like symptoms on 3/13/21 @ 0720 am. (Approx. 17 hrs post vaccination). Other symptoms include itching to face, headache, fatigue, pain behind the eyes and sore neck muscle. Took Motrin and Benadryl. Per HCW, symptoms worsened. On 03/14/21 @ 03:30am she noted swollen lips, injection site swelling, fever of 102 and shivering. She denied SOB, Chest pain. Had mild nausea and diarrhea (resolved). On 03/15/21, Sought treatment via PCP and was prescribed Alegra 180 mg by Mouth everyday and Ibuprofen 600 mg PO every 4-6 hours. OUTCOME: Began feeling better on 03/16/201 at approx. 1130 am. Continues to have a "knot" at injection site. Intermittent neck soreness and pain behind the eyes.

About 6 hours after receiving the shot I started experiencing skin sensitivity (common when I feel ill), chills, aches in my legs and a slight headache. The chills subsided after about 2 hours, but then my resting heart rate went up to 110-120 bpm rather than the normal 75-85 for me. It felt like my heart was beating out of my chest even though I was laying down in bed. That lasted through the night and I felt back to normal around mid-morning.
40 2021-03-19 redness After 15 minutes of sitting in the waiting area in case of adverse effects, (which I didn't have any... Read more
Close
After 15 minutes of sitting in the waiting area in case of adverse effects, (which I didn't have any) I went outside and sat in the parking lot for another 10 min. After no side effects, I drove away. Only to have a sudden reaction as I was driving. I've felt dizzy with flu vaccines before and have felt the same symptoms as with the covid vaccine when IV dye was injected for a CT scan 5 months ago. Felt faint/ dizzy, Got severe tachycardia, thought my heart was gonna explode. I drove back in a hurry, scared and confused. I was waiting to be seen, and no one ever came out. Symptoms subsided on their own after 15 min, therefore I just left without notifying anyone. 2 hours after vaccine, my arm looked moderately red and swollen, with minimal pain. 7 hours after getting the vaccine I started with chills and body aches. 8 hours after getting the vaccine I felt feverish and malaise. After taking Tylenol with feverish symptoms (didn't check temp) slept for 2 hours and felt a little better.

40 2021-03-22 rash, itchy skin, injection site pain I felt light headedness right away. The night that I got the injection, I felt kind of drunk. I felt... Read more
Close
I felt light headedness right away. The night that I got the injection, I felt kind of drunk. I felt like I had too much alcohol. I am very sensitive to things. I felt silly - loose - tired. In the night, I had aches and chills - no fever. The next day I felt achy and really really tired. I had a pain at the injection site. That evolved into a left side migraine (the achiness and fatigue and pain from shot) It created tension up my arm and up my neck - and I did get nausea with the headache - on Saturday. Sunday, I felt a little bit better but energy was still low - unusual tiredness; couldn't exercise as I felt a heavy fatigue. On Sunday, I went to a dance class but it was difficult as I was tired. On Monday, I felt a tiny bit better but still fatigued and did another dance class which went a little better. On Monday evening, I felt like I did the night of the injection - a little loopy and "drunk like." Monday night, I woke up with a Fiery, achy, itchy, burning rash on both of my arms and the tops of my legs. If I would itch it, it would exaggerate it. When I woke up the next day - the rash went everywhere in my body - it would come and go in different places - neck, face, down and up my legs and feet and on my butt. Pretty much every spot had the rash at one time or another. It was really bad on Tuesday morning, I called the doctor. Was treated with Benadryl and cortisone cream which helped with the symptoms. Tuesday night, it was excruciating - it was all up and down my legs, arms, neck and face and stomach and rear end and feet. It was very achy, burning and itchy - very intense. It would hurt if I scratched it. Accompanied with really intense fatigue. Wednesday, after taking Benadryl, I woke up and it was a tiny bit better. It was still on my legs, neck and face. Sometimes my arms would flare up and sometimes they wouldn't. Any kind of exertion - like my dance class - would trigger the rash - so I took a break from exercising that week. It started getting incrementally better - very slowly. Still there on Thursday - still fatigued and I was still taking Benadryl. Friday, also. Saturday, it was pretty much gone but it would threaten to come back and I felt itchiness in my legs when I went for a walk. It still feels a little lingering - my legs are itchy. I'm still building back my energy. Incrementally my energy is increasing. Still not 100% there but it's getting better day by day. Note: My history with my skin: I do get flare ups when I get bug bites and when I get poison ivy - I have very sensitive skin.
40 2021-03-23 injection site swelling, injection site pain, injection site warmth In addition to the known side effects of extreme fatigue, low grade fever and body aches, I also hav... Read more
Close
In addition to the known side effects of extreme fatigue, low grade fever and body aches, I also have right arm pain at the site of injection with right arm swelling, warmth and right axilla swelling and tenderness. The arm pain was began immediately at the time of injection and did initially lessen some for the first 12 hours until it started worsening mid-morning 22-24 hours after the injection. Around 26 hours after the injection the arm pain worsened such that it couldn't be ignored and the axilla pain became very prominent almost worse than the arm pain. Upon inspection I noticed obvious swelling and pain in my right axilla. The right arm and axilla pain has persisted and worsened over the last 2 days to now include upper biceps, upper triceps, lower deltoid, trapezius, clavicular and right lateral breast pain. The axilla and arm swelling has persisted and worsened over the last two days to now include swelling in my upper arm, around my clavicle, my upper chest and upper back. The initial axilla swelling has not decreased any and is more prominent than any of the swelling located elsewhere. Of note, I cannot easily palpate any axilla, clavicular or cervical lymph nodes. If there is lymp involvement the nodes are not appearing to be extremely swollen with palpation exam.

40 2021-04-06 hives, skin discoloration from altered blood flow, itchy skin, rash, rash with redness, rash macular During 15 min waiting period around 0945 at vaccination site, patient became flushed and had increas... Read more
Close
During 15 min waiting period around 0945 at vaccination site, patient became flushed and had increased heart rate of 106 bpm at rest per patient's Apple iWatch. Provider onsite was notified and immediately evaluated the patient. Instructed patient to remove face mask to allow ease of breathing. Heart rate returned to normal for patient (68bpm) within a couple of minutes. Patient stated she informed the provider that she was feeling better and was cleared to return to work. Patient states that throughout the day, she was mentally "foggy", sleepy, yawning frequently. States at around 1300, she began to itch on her arms, then around 1400 she noticed her arms were blotchy with purple/white rash. In areas where she scratched, she reports the rash was dark red with a bit of orange tint. Reports legs had rash that appeared has hives. Patient also reports that about 1-2 hours post vaccination, she started having chest tightness and shortness of breath. At 1600 she called the clinic and spoke with a medic on the phone. She informed him of her symptoms (chest tightness, shortness of breath and full body rash and hives). She was instructed by medic to report to the nearest ER for evaluation and treatment. Patient states that she did not feel that she needed to go to ER at that time. She states that at 1800 she took Benadryl which did not seem to help the symptoms however she states they did not worsen. She took a second dose of Benadryl at 2200 and fell asleep. Patient states when she woke up this morning at 0600, all symptoms had resolved. She denies any symptoms now except for some minor itching on a couple areas of her wrist, ankle and under arm. No full body rash or hives noted. Denies any further administration of Benadryl at this time, as of 1630 on 7 APR 2021.

Patient reports the night of the vaccine, she had chills and low grade fever (100.7F) that resolved by morning and she was tired for two days. On March 29, 2021, she had discomfort on the left axillary and left upper back areas which help like her "shirt was too tight and rubbing" and the upper back was like a "pinch" and she continues to have this. She developed a rash under her left arm on April 2 in the evening and it continued to spread and erupt across her upper back and chest. April 4, 2021, she developed blisters and it continued to spread down her left arm. She contacted her PCP and MD on April 4, 2021. After describing the symptoms to MD, MD prescribed Acyclovir 800 mg PO 5 x daily x 10 days and gabapentin 300 mg PO TID. MD advised patient that she likely had herpes zoster. She reports she improved 40% with treatment and presented for evaluation 5 days after contacting MD and the diagnosis was confirmed.

Around 1pm, my mild headache started to intensify and had ringing in my ears that would repeatedly come and go (still is doing so today, just not as frequent). Around 4pm is when all of the "normal" side effects started?chills, hot flashes, sore arm, and super sleepy. I woke up a couple hours later, with a headache that was WAY worse and was super nauseous. The ear/jaw pain was more than I could stand - had it in both ears, but the right ear was more intense. It felt like I had a lighting rod between both ears and had these intense "zings" that kept going back and forth, like they were playing ping-pong. The painful "zings" reminded me of those felt during an ear infection but WAY MORE INTENSE. My jaw was super tight, as well, with a horribly intense headache. I spent the entire night night doing warm compresses on my ears, taking Tylenol every 4-6 hours, staying in the shower, and lots of crying. It was so bad that I felt the need to go to the ER but didn't feel comfortable driving and didn't want to go the ambulance route?and thought it was pointless because going to the ER for ear pain would leave me there for hours and hours since I didn't feel it would be viewed an an urgent emergency. My goal was to make it through the night and see if I could get into my PCP doctor the following morning. I took another Tylenol around 5am, and I thankfully cried myself to sleep for a couple of hours. When I woke up, I called my PCP but couldn't get in, so I did an online doctor visit through my insurance company. My fever was about 103.06 at its highest during the night but was gone by 3:34pm Friday afternoon (assuming because I was taking more Tylenol than I had been post-online doctor's appointment). Around 7pm Friday evening, I knew I needed to go to the ER or urgent care. I got a ride and was taken to urgent care for my intense ear pain. They gave me a Toradol injection and Tramadol prescription. By bedtime Friday night, the injection was doing its job and made the ear pain and zings were much less intense (didn't get the prescription until a couple days later). On March 20, Saturday night, is when I developed a red, itchy rash on my back and tummy. Over the next couple of days, it was on my chest, arms, legs?pretty much come and was in various places. I called my PCP Monday morning (March 22), left a message, and they called me back to tell me to restart taking my Zyrtec/HCL to see if it would help the itching. It has and am just mildly breaking out at this time. The stinkin' ear/jaw pain returned on Tuesday the 23rd, so I loaded up on OTC ear drops and made an appointment with my PCP for Wednesday, March 24. She saw no ear infection and essentially told me to keep taking the pain meds. I received the vaccine on March 18 and did not return to work until the following Thursday. In retrospect, I should have just missed the remainder of that week, too.

41 2021-05-27 injection site redness, injection site discomfort, injection site rash THE PATIENT CAME TO THE PHARMACY TO BE VACCINATED FOR COVID-19, WITH JOHNSON & JOHNSON, ON FRIDAY, M... Read more
Close
THE PATIENT CAME TO THE PHARMACY TO BE VACCINATED FOR COVID-19, WITH JOHNSON & JOHNSON, ON FRIDAY, MAY 21, 2021 AT ROUGHLY 2PM. I GAVE HER THE VACCINATION IN HER DELTOID MUSCLE ON HER LEFT ARM. SHE ALMOST IMMEDIATELY COMPLAINED OF DISCOMFORT AND ASKED IF I HAD A COLD PACK. I PROVIDED HER WITH ONE, WHICH SHE USED WHILE WAITING THE 15 MINUTE POST-VACCINATION OBSERVATION TIME. SHE LEFT THE PHARMACY WITHOUT INCIDENT. ONLY A COUPLE HOURS LATER, SHE CALLED THE PHARMACY TO REPORT ERYTHEMA AT AND AROUND THE INJECTION SITE. I DID NOT KNOW AT THAT TIME WHETHER THE ERYTHEMA WAS DUE TO THE COLD PACK OR IF IT WAS A VACCINE-INDUCED RASH, SO I INSTRUCTED HER TO TAKE A DOSE OF ANTIHISTAMINE. AS SHE HAD CETIRIZINE IN THE HOUSE, SHE TOOK THAT. SHE WAS HOME WITH HER HUSBAND. I RECOMMENDED HE KEEP AN EYE ON HER AND IF SHE DEVELOPED ANY ADDITIONAL SYMPTOMS OR WORSENING RASH, SHE SHOULD GO TO THE HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION. ADDITIONAL SYMPTOMS INCLUDED SWELLING, TROUBLE BREATHING, WHEEZING, CHEST OR THROAT TIGHTNESS, OR HIVES. THOUGH SHE DID NOT EXPERIENCE ADDITIONAL SYMPTOMS, SHE DECIDED TO GO TO UCONN HEALTH CENTER ER IN FARMINGTON. THEY DID BELIEVE THE RASH WAS VACCINE-INDUCED BUT DID NOT FEEL SHE REQUIRED ANY ADDITIONAL TREATMENT AND DISCHARGED HER (I.E., NO EPINEPHRINE). THE PATIENT NOTED THAT HER BLOOD PRESSURE AT THE ER WAS HIGHER THAN "HER NORMAL" AT 152/95. THE FOLLOWING TWO DAYS, THE RASH STAYED THE SAME AND WAS DESCRIBED BY THE PATIENT AS THE "WORST SUNBURN SHE'S EVER HAD". SHE ALSO HAD NORMAL SIDE EFFECTS OF BODY ACHES AND CHILLS/SWEATS. ON MONDAY, 5/24/21, SHE FOLLOWED UP WITH HER PCP. HE AGREED WITH THE HOSPITAL THAT THE RASH WAS VACCINE-INDUCED AND TOLD HER THAT HE DIDN'T WANT HER GETTING ANY COVID-19 VACCINES IN THE FUTURE. HE DID BLOODWORK TO RULE OUT PLATELET ISSUES, WHICH, PER PATIENT, WERE NORMAL; SHE NOTED THAT HER RBC'S AND HEMATOCRIT WERE SLIGHTLY ELEVATED. HER PCP GAVE HER A MEDROL DOSEPAK FOR THE RASH. THE PATIENT IS RECOVERING. I BELIEVE IT IS WORTH NOTING, HOWEVER, THAT THE PATIENT APPLIED THE COLD PACK DIRECTLY TO HER ARM FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME AND DID NOT PROVIDE THIS INFORMATION TO EITHER THE ER OR HER PCP. SHE SENT ME A PHOTO OF HER ARM WHICH SHOWS GENERALIZED ERYTHEMA (THE SIZE OF THE COLD PACK) - THE ONLY PART THAT IS COMPLETELY NORMAL IS THE SKIN BELOW THE BAND-AID. I BELIEVE THE PATIENT CREATED AN ICE BURN BY USING A COLD PACK TOO DIRECTLY, FOR TOO LONG, AND THAT THE UNDER BAND-AID AREA WAS NOT RED BECAUSE IT PROTECTED THE SKIN FROM COLD BURN. I SUGGESTED TO THE PATIENT THAT SHE RUN THIS THEORY BY HER PCP, AS I BELIEVE IT IS IMPORTANT "MISSING INFORMATION", THAT COULD POTENTIALLY CHANGE THE DIAGNOSIS AND ALTER HIS RECOMMENDATION TO AVOID FUTURE COVID VACCINATION. WHETHER OR NOT THE PATIENT CONTACTED HIM AGAIN IS UNKNOWN.

41 2021-06-10 injection site pain About ten minutes after leaving the vaccination site, I began feeling a strange dizziness; an intern... Read more
Close
About ten minutes after leaving the vaccination site, I began feeling a strange dizziness; an internal wobbly-Jello-like sensation. I felt a pin/needle/ stabbing sensation on my left fingers, particularly on the dorsal side of the third and fourth fingers, and in the middle of the tongue. The tongue felt as if was receiving a subtle electric charge that immobilized it with every shock. It lasted about 5 minutes. My vision was blurry. After that, my mind was foggy. At about midnight, flu-like symptoms began sudden, but they were the expected symptoms for a covid vaccine (fever, body aches, sweats, sore throat, severe headache, pain on injection site, etc.) However, the pin/needle/ stabbing sensation was felt throughout the body. It sometimes felt as if a bubble, waves, or something was moving inside of me, in different areas of the body (rib cage, legs, chest, arms, legs, face, and top of the head (like when a baby moves inside of a pregnant woman, without the visible bump). My body, head, and neck felt stiff. Symptoms were milder after 48 hours, on and off, until 4/13/2021 when I felt a sunken feeling, like something dropped inside of me (sugar, blood pressure, blood rush, I do not know). The tense feeling of the body returned. I felt dizzy. Left arm and leg felt tingly. There were palpitations, but I think that it was due to being scared about all the other symptoms. I felt cold and was shivering. The head felt stiff again. I was very thirsty. In the following days, symptoms got milder. On 4/22/2021, at about 4pm, the sunken feeling returned, along with the dizziness, wave or bubble-like sensation through head, face, body. The wave-like sensation flashed across my face, head, and neck intermittently. It was hard to speak, pronounce words, and swallow. The tongue felt numb. It lasted about two hours. I felt exhausted, so I took a nap until 8pm. When I woke up, I felt like nothing had happened, no symptoms until 1:00 am. At 1:00 pm, 4/23/2021, the sunken feeling, dizziness, palpitations, heavy breathing without shortness of breath, cold/shiver, blurred vision, the wave-like sensation, and pokes suddenly returned. The waves were more intense and felt like pressure on the right side of the head and left side of the chest. Went to the Emergency Room. With every wave of sensations, was accompanied by an urgency to urinate. I urinated like 3 times in a span of 30 to 45 minutes (full bladder). Findings were normal but symptoms continued through 4/24/2021, on and off. Each episode lasts anywhere from 1 to 4 hours. Short lasting, mild symptoms returned Monday 04/26/2021, at night, until Wednesday 04/27. However, that Wednesday night, I felt a belt like, tight sensation around the left bicep and neck. It felt as if I was being grabbed by the left arm. On 4/29/2021, around 5:00 pm, I called an ambulance because all symptoms had returned ?full force?, such as sunken feeling, blurred vision, dizziness (like passing out), intense head and left chest pressure (in waves, like having a huge fish or parasite inside the chest and head), numb mouth (like dental anesthesia), hard to speak (hard time sending the message from brain to mouth). It took great effort to speak and felt that I had to decide whether continue speaking or staying conscious. I also had blurred vision with the first sunken feeling. Symptoms continued 2 to 3 times a day. Since 4/29 a feeling of being inside of an elevator, airplane, or earthquake, and the numbness on the left side of chest and arm remain, even when no other symptoms are present. Also, both arms become numb while sleeping, every night, multiple times a night, since 4/29. Since then, I sleep on 3 pillows (two in my head, one on the shoulders to create an angle) to minimize the numbness of the arms and the head/neck pressure while sleeping. On 5/5/21, symptoms began while car riding as a passenger and upper body felt tight. Strangely, symptoms ended when car stopped moving. Later that day, while walking through a department store, nostrils felt uneven, as if the left nostil were breathing cold air while the right was taking warm air. That night, symptoms intensified (the attack). Like all other times, urinating was too frequent while ?the attack? is present. This time, my body felt sore and tired (Flu-like). There was an intense pressure on the right side of the eye and forehead. The neck stiffness was intense. For the past two weeks, ?attacks? have been less frequent, about 2 to 3 times a week, lasting a maximum of 2 hours. The numbness on the left side of the chest and arm continues. The feeling of something moving or pins/needles may appear sporadically throughout the day. At times, they feel like twitches. The woozy feeling of being inside of an elevator remains. Breathing still feels heavy, like trying to breathe with the face in front of a fan. All test results from the 2 ER visits were normal, including the CT scan. A brain MRI, done on 5/5, was also normal. A 24-hour heart monitor also had normal results.

Prednisone 60 mg by mouth given 12:29 PM NEUROLOGY CONSULT NOTE Assessment: Formulation- Diagnosis is guarded. Localization structurally would suggest subcortical (thalamic) or small brain-stem in a sensory territory on the right. Etiologies could be stroke given her vascular risk factors but seems unlikely given there is stereotypy of earlier symptomatology. Demyelinating would be another possibility as well, but again, the stereotype. Seizure unlikely because of the timing of rush from toes to body was minutes and duration of some occasions being days. Complicated migraine possible, has some risk factors, but should be treated as dx of exclusion. She does make complaint of headache, which could support. Some FND elaboration on her anxiety-ridden allergic reaction is also possible, but no objective non-structural signs to support.

54 2021-04-13 shingles Within a few hours after the vaccine was administered, I felt unwell and became progressively worse.... Read more
Close
Within a few hours after the vaccine was administered, I felt unwell and became progressively worse. For 36 hours after the vaccine, I experienced a crisis of energy, fatigue, and body soreness. It subsided after 36 hours. I expected that was a reasonable response for my already highly sensitive and overactive immune system (autoimmunity). What I didn't expect was two weeks later to erupt with shingles. I have had shingles twice in my earlier adult life, so I am familiar with the symptoms. This course has gotten worse over the last 2-1/2 weeks. There was no other change in my low-stress life with the exception of the Covid vaccine. I had been working hard to reduce my inflammation already with diet and lifestyle changes for the last 2 years with great success. It seems the vaccine triggered my immune system in such a profound way it pulled this dormant virus out. I was concerned to get the vaccine because of my autoimmunity but decided to do it anyway, hoping for the best. I don't know if it's advisable for people with existing immune conditions to tax their system this way. I know I'm paying a high price.

Close
4/5/2021--Received Janssen vaccine. Felt very hot during the day. 4/6/2021--Woke up with very bad headache and rash on the injected arm plus on my stomach. Went for a walk and felt pain in my left calf and achilles tendon. Went to work. 4/7/2021--Started my work day as a Personal Trainer/Fitness Instructor at 6am as usual. Taught cycling classes and trained a few clients. Went for walk. Still had a headache. When I got in my car to head home, my vision was super blurry and I felt very dizzy. I ate an orange and peanuts and hydrated more. I was not even sure I could drive home. I got home told my family how I was feeling. My husband noticed my eyes were very red and swollen. I took a shower, drank a smoothie and ate a salad. Used my aunt's BP cuff to check my BP and it was 148/99. I have NEVER had HBP. 4/8/21--Woke up feeling disoriented as if the left side of my face, body were off--neurological stuff. I went to reach for grapes in the refrigerator and could not grab them. I felt like I have never felt before and ask my husband to drive me to the ER. While at the waiting room at the ER, I felt chest tightness and pain and nauseous. My BP was 153/111. Again, I have never been diagnosed or been treated for hypertension. They did EKG, lab tests, chest X-ray. Once my BP came down, they sent me home. This is before all the JJ Janssen vaccine "news" came out and the reasons it was paused. I developed a very bad cough about two hours after I got home from the ER. 4/9/11--Made appointment with a brand new primary care doctor. Saw her on Monday 4/12/2021 as recommended by ER. I had never met her before. She prescribed a very low dose of BP medication, which I did not take because the number one side-effect is dry-cough. I was already coughing a lot, later on with blood. 4/11/2021--Still feeling pretty bad, I woke up to the news of the Janssen vaccine being paused. Frankly, I felt relieved that I was not going crazy. This truly has been one of the hardest things I have ever gone (and still am) going through. I became concerned about the pain in the left calf and heel could be a clot. Called primary care doctor. Had ultrasound of legs and chest x-ray the following day 4/12/2021--Had persistent cough with blood. Went to ER at 9pm. Had EKG, blood work, CT without contrast of chest, covid test--negative. Got home around 2am. 4/19/21--Followed up with primary care doctor who after explaining to her I am extremely fatigued, still blurry vision, dizzy, cough better but not gone, chest discomfort on the left side, she referred me to an ophtamologist and cardiologist. My insurance and this poorly established referral system is very difficult to navigate. Up to now I am still waiting for the referral and pre-aurhtorization to the opthtamologist. (4/23/2021). I want to say, I am pretty healthy. I have worked in fitness and wellness for over 30 years. I have never drank alcohol, smoked or done any drugs. Prior to this no physician has told me I have HBP or any issues for which I have to be medicated. I take zero medications. Even when I had the bad headache from the vaccine I took nothing. I have not worked in two weeks and had not driven until last saturday. If I don't work, I don't get paid. I pay for almost $600/month for my insurance in the marketplace. This has been another stressor of this storm. Getting providers to really listen and insurance companies to take situations like this seriously. I could not drive at night. This has been rough and I look forward to being myself soon. This reaction felt like a heart attack/stroke with extreme fatigue, acid reflux, cough with some blood, muscular pain. The rash and headaches were the least of my concerns. I am not yet recovered from all of this. I sure hope there is no permanent damage and that this too shall pass. It is important to note that I have tried reporting this event several times to the VAERS website online. I completed the 4-5 pages multiple times and it would not let me submit. I also called the VAERS 1-800 number to report and they told me to go back to the online form. I left several messages when I could not get it done online and to this date no one has called me back. I called to report my adverse reaction and they told me they do not take that info. I also called the health dept. After several phone calls to them a nurse called me back but did not take a formal report. When someone is feeling pretty sick, this is a lot to ask of. I persisted because I feel this is important to be reported.

My appointment was on time, 4pm on 4/3 at the Pharmacy. The young girl that gave me the shot told me she was certified, and she gave me the shot in the presence of her manager. I have given myself shots for years with diabetes, plus many flu shots, and have never felt pain like that. I expressed this to her, how painful it was, and she just said "I know, I know..." as if it was normal for the shot to be so painful. I knew instantly something was wrong. They were more worried, it seemed, about a potential adverse reaction such as an allergy shock, since I'm allergic to a few things, but I did not experience that. I waited 15 minutes, my arm hurting the whole time, and they suggested I go buy Tylenol for the pain, which I did. My left arm has hurt since then. I got a horrible bruise from this shot (will send picture) that took weeks to heal. Since then I've continued to feel pain and don't have full mobility of my left arm. I can type, but not lifting anything heavy and have to go easy with anything on the left side. I thought at first it might be what people were calling "covid arm" but I discovered that was more about soreness, not pain. I tried ibuprofin, but after three weeks I'd had enough and made a doctors appointment. Since I was also noticing my left shoulder was very tense and tight, and I was starting to get neck stiffness in same area, I started googling before my appointment. When I entered my symptoms, SIRVA kept popping up, so I wondered if that was what I now had because of the improper vaccine administration. I asked my doctor for an MRI order to find out, but she said we needed to do an Xray first (which only showed mild issues related to osteo). She offered a prescription of taking Advil 400 mg three times and day and to use a muscle relaxer when I needed it, such as at night (Cyclobenzaprine). She said to try that for a week, and if it wasn't better, that another Dr could order MRI. Since then I've also added a pain spot under my left shoulder blade. Insurance called and said the order was "under review" so that's where things stand now. If they don't approve, I guess I will go next to an orthopedist for guidance? This has cost me health, due to lack of sleep also - I wake up with pain in the middle of the night, even when I take the meds. Praying for a diagnosis, and solution, soon.

Prior to receiving her COVID-19 vaccine, the patient was already having symptoms from anxiety/nervousness about the vaccine. Patient was given her injection and within 1-2 minutes, she began feeling dizzy and lightheaded. The vaccine administrator came to me (pharmacist on duty) to notify me that she was not feeling well. I went to go check on her and she stated that she felt as though she was going to faint. I advised her to stay seated, asked if she would like an ice pack and water, and stepped out to get those for her while remaining vigilant (because I wanted to be in the same room as her for observation/safety). I brought her the ice pack, she held it on her chest and head and said it felt nice. After about a minute I stepped out again to ask a technician to get a water for her. When I came back, the patient was still seated but had a blank stare and her mouth was slightly open. I repeated her name out loud and nudged her shoulder several times, however the patient was unresponsive completely. I immediately looked for the red emergency kit in the consultation room but did not see one (I later found out that there was an EpiPen on the table in the room, but I did not see it at the time due to the urgency of the situation). I rushed back into the pharmacy, told the technicians to call 911, and took an EpiPen off the shelf in the pharmacy. I ran back into the room and the patient's face was very red, her eyes were bulging slightly, and it looked like she was trying to reach her hand up or move it, but was unable to. I injected her with the EpiPen immediately, and within roughly 5 seconds she came back to consciousness and looked at me and said "I'm sorry". EMS arrived extremely fast and was there a few minutes after using the EpiPen. She was then taken by ambulance to the hospital. Patient had a friend, with her at the store who was scheduled to receive the vaccine as well, but after the incident she decided otherwise. Later that evening I gave patient's friend a phone call to check and see how patient was doing, and to also let her know that patient's vaccination card was at the pharmacy if she wanted to pick it up. That evening around 6:30-7pm, patient's husband came to the pharmacy to get her card, he updated us that she was being discharged from the hospital and that she was okay.

At 23 hours post Johnson and Johnson vaccination, I began to have a 10/10 headache (which was the worst headache of my life), nausea and severe aura. I then became extremely confused and was taken to the emergency department by my husband. The following was reported to me the next day when I awoke in the ICU at Hospital: within an hour of arriving at the ED, I exhibited a progressive hyperactive delirium, agitation, slurred speech (word salad), combativeness, confabulation, word finding difficulties and an inability to follow commands. The neurologist in the ED said that she was seeing this adverse vaccination side effect in other patients at the 24-hour period. I received Haldol, Zyprexa, and Ativan to control the delirium and received a head CT angiogram in the ED, which was normal. I was transferred by ambulance to the main hospital due to acute metabolic encephalopathy/altered mental status. I was admitted to the neurological unit whereby I became critically hypotensive (60s over 30s) and was transferred to the ICU due to persistent hypotension unresponsive to IV normal saline. I was then transferred and admitted to the ICU and was given continued IV fluid resuscitation and Levophed vasopressor. I was eventually weaned from vasopressors and was discharged back home in three days exhausted, bruised, fatigued and with continuous clouded mentation. I have been told by all of the doctors that this was a vaccination side-effect, which caused cerebritis. I was subsequently treated as an outpatient at Hospital for intractable aura with IV Valporic Acid, Magnesium, and Lasix infusion on April 1, 2021.
